Spark's execution model.

It starts at the top, with the driver. The driver is the brain of the job. It takes your code and builds a plan.

That plan is a directed acyclic graph, a dag. Think of it as a map of every transformation, in the order they depend on one another.

Spark then cuts that map into stages. A stage is a run of work that can happen without shuffling data across the network. Here the plan splits into stage one and stage two.

Each stage becomes a set of tasks, and here is the important part: there is one task per partition of data. Tasks are the smallest unit of work.

Finally those tasks are handed down to the executors. Executors are the workers out on the cluster, and they run the tasks in parallel. That is how a single line of code becomes work flowing across many machines.
